r b minus k times the other. So depending on which is larger.\n\nFrom state (4,3): max is already  cycles?\n\nWait starting pair is (4,3).\n\nStan subtract x: either 4 -k*3 or 3 -k*4?\n\nBut needs non-negative result.\n\nIf he subtracts 3*1 from 4: resulting (1, 3). Valid.\n\nIf he subtracts 4\'s multiple from 3: non-positive? 3 - something: no.\n\nSo only option is subtract k=1 of 3 from 4.\n\nSo new position (1, 3).\n\nOllie now has (1,3).\n\nNext move: Ollie can subtract:\n\nEither subtract multiple of 1 from 3: result could be (1, 3 -k*1); must make non-negative and make something leading toward reaching zero.\n\nIf he subtracts k=3, but holding that though:\n\nWait from pair (1,3):\n\nOllie can either subtract multiples of 1 from 3 or 3 from 1?\n\nWait the rule is "subtract any positive multiple of one integer from the other". So you can subtract from the larger to the smaller.\n\nSince 3 >1, Ollie can subtract k*1 from 3 multiple times.\n\nShe can subtract any integer k ≥1 times such that 3 -k*1 ≥0.\n\nPossible moves:\n\nIf Ollie subtracts k= 3 times 1 from 3, yielding 0 and 1? Then state becomes (1, 0). Then the win condition is when a number is zero. So if a becomes 0, and the other non-zero number? Let me see:\n\nIf the state is (1,0). Then the next player (Stan next) can move by subtracting k* something.\n\nWait according to the rule, if any number becomes zero, the game wins. So if someone moves and resulting number 0 is achieved by making one of the numbers zero.\n\nSo in this case, from (1,3), for Ollie subtracting k*1 from 3:\n\nIf she subtracts 3 times: 3-3*1 =0. So new pair is (1, 0). Therefore Ollie would make the previous numbers (3 - 3*1,1) = (1, 0)? Wait wait, let\'s clarify:\n\nWait from (a, b), is a = 3 and b =1? Wait wait I think I need to clarify initial pair is (x,y) where x is the bigger one.\n\nWait let\'s retrace: previous state after Stan takes 4-3=1, making numbers (1, 3). Now it\'s Ollie\'s turn.\n\nOptions for Ollie:\n\nCan Ollie subt